# Question 1

## Tidy up the data


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuIyByZW1vdmUgdW5uZWNlc3NhcnkgY29sdW1uc1xua2NfaG91c2luZ190cmltIDwtIGtjX2hvdXNpbmcgJT4lIFxuICBzZWxlY3QoLWMoZGF0ZSwgaWQsIHNxZnRfbGl2aW5nMTUsIHNxZnRfbG90MTUsIHppcGNvZGUpKVxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
# remove unnecessary columns
kc_housing_trim <- kc_housing %>% 
  select(-c(date, id, sqft_living15, sqft_lot15, zipcode))
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


## Change waterfront & yr_renovated to logical variables


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxua2NfaG91c2luZ190cmltIDwtIGtjX2hvdXNpbmdfdHJpbSAlPiUgXG4gIG11dGF0ZSh3YXRlcmZyb250ID0gYXMubG9naWNhbCh3YXRlcmZyb250KSxcbiAgICAgICAgIHJlbm92YXRlZCA9IGFzLmxvZ2ljYWwoeXJfcmVub3ZhdGVkKSkgJT4lIFxuICBzZWxlY3QoLXlyX3Jlbm92YXRlZClcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
kc_housing_trim <- kc_housing_trim %>% 
  mutate(waterfront = as.logical(waterfront),
         renovated = as.logical(yr_renovated)) %>% 
  select(-yr_renovated)
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


Have a think about how to treat `condition` and `grade`? Are they interval or categorical ordinal data types?


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuIyBjaGFuZ2UgY29uZGl0aW9uICYgZ3JhZGUgdG8gZmFjdG9yIHR5cGVcbmtjX2hvdXNpbmdfdHJpbSA8LSBrY19ob3VzaW5nX3RyaW0gJT4lIFxuICBtdXRhdGUoY29uZGl0aW9uID0gYXMuZmFjdG9yKGNvbmRpdGlvbikpICU+JSBcbiAgbXV0YXRlKGdyYWRlID0gYXMuZmFjdG9yKGdyYWRlKSlcblxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
# change condition & grade to factor type
kc_housing_trim <- kc_housing_trim %>% 
  mutate(condition = as.factor(condition)) %>% 
  mutate(grade = as.factor(grade))

```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

# First Predictor


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin  -->

```r
# add sqft_living as first predictor for price
mod1a <- lm(price ~ sqft_living, data = kc_housing_trim)

#take log of each variable to scale better
mod1b <- lm(log(price) ~ log(sqft_living), data = kc_housing_trim)
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


## Diagnostic Plots


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYXV0b3Bsb3QobW9kMWEpXG5gYGAifQ== -->

```r
autoplot(mod1a)
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-plot-begin eyJoZWlnaHQiOjQzMi42MzI5LCJ3aWR0aCI6NzAwLCJzaXplX2JlaGF2aW9yIjowLCJjb25kaXRpb25zIjpbXX0= -->

<img src="data:image/png;base64," />

<!-- rnb-plot-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


__Interpretation__

In its original format as price ~ sqft_living, my model appears to fail on tests
of all our assumptions. In the normal QQ plot It does not appear to of a normal 
distribution (perhaps right skewed) and it does not hold on constancy of 
variation. The scale-location plot shows evidence of heteroscedasticity.

To remedy this I have taken the log of each variable in order to scale them so
that they may better meet our assumptions. The new plots do appear to show
improvement. The residuals vs fitted shows better variation in our residuals,
it also follows a normal distribution on our normal QQ plot better. The points
no longer show a funnel shape in the scale-location and appear to show
better variation in residuals.
